<br>
You want my honest viewpoint on this?  Said it before and I will say it again.  EQ is not well-suited as a game to role-playing.  Now, a dedicated role-player can rise above the inconsistances in the game design, but rising above something and avoiding it all together are two different things.  Going after Paladins because they loot the fallen?  Why not pick a more universal and common role-playing fault?  How about you accuse everyone who continues to play after dying of not role-playing?  Properly done, they should really go and make new characters after each death. :/<br>
<br>
This game cannot be role-played on every level.  You will run into things that are impossible to deal with without rewriting the basic laws of existance to allow for the absurdities of the game.  Why is it three mushrooms are always standing on the exact same damn spot in Dawnshroud when I know I've killed them each 200 times?  Why do I run madly for a specific line in a mountain pass, confident that if I can make it there the massive giant that is chasing me will give up?  How come if I make 500 fish rolls I'll learn how to bake bread?<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> How the hell do I run clear across the continent of Antonica without ever sleeping!?!</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Role-playing properly does not mean trying to make sense of the non-sensical, or allow for it on every level of character portrayal.  Role-playing means making the best of it within the aspects of the game where it is realistically possible.  Asking more that that from yourself is self-destructive to your enjoyment of the game, and asking more than that of other people is unreasonable to the point of being damn near anti-social.<br>
